0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">15. LEGAL PROCEEDINGS</font><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">We and certain current and former officers and directors have been named as defendants in complaints filed by investors in the United States District Court for the District of Colorado. The first complaint was filed in November&nbsp;2007 and several other complaints were filed shortly thereafter. These actions were consolidated and, in September&nbsp;2008, the district court appointed a lead plaintiff and counsel. An amended consolidated complaint was filed in December&nbsp;2008. The amended complaint purports to state claims under Section&nbsp;10(b), 20(a), and 20A of the Exchange Act on behalf of a class of all persons who purchased our common stock between April&nbsp;2, 2007 and April&nbsp;14, 2008 (the &#x201C;Class&nbsp;Period&#x201D;). The amended complaint also added our independent auditor as a defendant. The amended complaint alleges that, during the Class&nbsp;Period, the defendants made false and misleading public statements about us and our business and prospects and, as a result, the market price of our common stock was artificially inflated. The amended complaint also claims that certain current and former officers and directors traded in our common stock on the basis of material non-public information. The amended complaint seeks compensatory damages on behalf of the alleged class in an unspecified amount, including interest, and also added attorneys&#x2019; fees and costs of litigation. On February&nbsp;28, 2011, the District Court granted motions to dismiss filed by the defendants and dismissed all claims. A final judgment was thereafter entered. Plaintiffs subsequently appealed to the United States Court of Appeals for the Tenth Circuit.&nbsp; We and those current and former officers and directors named as defendants have entered into a Stipulation of Settlement with the plaintiffs that would, if approved by the United States District Court for the District of Colorado, resolve all claims asserted against us by the plaintiffs on behalf of the putative class, and plaintiffs&#x2019; appeal would be dismissed. Our independent auditor is not a party to the Stipulation of Settlement. The Stipulation of Settlement received preliminary approval from the District Court on August&nbsp;28, 2013.&nbsp; It remains subject to customary conditions, including final court approval following notice to stockholders. On February 13, 2014 a final settlement hearing took place and the parties are awaiting a ruling in conjunction with the same.&nbsp;&nbsp;If the settlement becomes final, all amounts required by the settlement will be paid by our insurers. There can be no assurance that the settlement will be finally approved by the District Court, or that approval by the District Court will, if challenged, be upheld by the Tenth Circuit. </font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">On October&nbsp;27, 2010, Spectrum Agencies (&#x201C;Spectrum&#x201D;) filed suit against our subsidiary, Crocs Europe B.V. (&#x201C;Crocs Europe&#x201D;), in the High Court of Justice, Queen&#x2019;s Bench Division, Royal Courts of Justice in London, United Kingdom (&#x201C;UK&#x201D;). Spectrum acted as an agent for Crocs products in the UK from 2005 until Crocs Europe terminated the relationship on July&nbsp;3, 2008 due to Spectrum&#x2019;s breach of its duty to act in good faith towards Crocs Europe. Spectrum alleges that Crocs Europe unlawfully terminated the agency relationship and failed to pay certain sales commissions. A trial on the liability, not quantum (compensation and damages), was held at the High Court in London from November&nbsp;30, 2011 to December&nbsp;5, 2011. On December&nbsp;16, 2011, the High Court of Justice issued a judgment that found that although Spectrum&#x2019;s actions were a breach of its duty to act in good faith towards Crocs Europe the breach was not sufficiently severe to justify termination. We believe that the trial judge erred in his findings and subsequently appealed the judgment.&nbsp; On October&nbsp;30, 2012, the Court of Appeal handed down its judgment confirming the trial judge&#x2019;s findings. We submitted a request to the Supreme Court seeking permission to appeal.&nbsp; On April&nbsp;24, 2013 the Supreme Court declined to grant permission to appeal.&nbsp; Given that to date the legal proceedings in this case have only addressed liability, there have been no findings in relation to the amount of compensation or damages other than with respect to legal fees. Under English law, the prevailing party is entitled to reimbursement of reasonable legal fees incurred in the proceedings. The trial of&nbsp;liability and quantum were split by the&nbsp;Court&nbsp;in the interests of case management. The&nbsp;alleged quantum of damages&nbsp;has not been&nbsp;fully&nbsp;pleaded out and will be assessed as part of the forthcoming damages phase.&nbsp; A trial and judgment on dama</font><font style="display: inline;">ges is expected in approximately 12</font><font style="display: inline;"> months.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">We are currently subject to an audit by U.S. Customs&nbsp;&amp; Border Protection (&#x201C;CBP&#x201D;) in respect of the period from 2006 to 2010.&nbsp; In the course of the audit, we identified certain valuation errors and tendered ap</font><font style="display: inline;">proximately </font><font style="display: inline;">$1.4</font><font style="display: inline;"> million in additional duties. Subsequently, we identified additional value errors which will require the payment of additional duties totaling approximately </font><font style="display: inline;">$0.7</font><font style="display: inline;"> million. The exact amount of this additional tender is subject to verification by CBP.&nbsp;&nbsp;In October&nbsp;2013, CBP issued an audit report to which we filed comments and objections.&nbsp; CBP has projected unpaid duties totaling approximately </font><font style="display: inline;">$12.4</font><font style="display: inline;"> million in connec</font><font style="display: inline;">tion with various classification errors during the period under review.&nbsp; We have responded that these projections are erroneous and provided arguments that demonstrate the amount due in connection with this matter is considerably less than the amount projected.&nbsp; CBP is currently reviewing this response.&nbsp; It is not possible at this time to predict whether our arguments will be successful in eliminating or reducing the amount in dispute.&nbsp; At this time, it is not possible to determine when a formal notice of claim will be received from CBP</font><font style="display: inline;">. &nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">Likewise, it is not possible to predict whether CBP may seek to assert a claim for penalties in addition to any unpaid duties. </font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">Mexico&#x2019;s Federal Tax Authority (&#x201C;SAT&#x201D;) audited the period from January&nbsp;2006 to July&nbsp;2011.&nbsp; There were two phases to the audit, the first for capital equipment and finished goods and the second for raw materials.&nbsp; The first phase was completed and no major discrepancies were noted by the SAT.&nbsp; On January&nbsp;9, 2013, Crocs received a notice for the second phase in which the SAT issued a tax assessment (taxes and penalties) of roughl</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">y &nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">280.0</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million pesos (approximately </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">$22.0</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million) based on the value of all of Crocs&#x2019; imported raw materials during the audit period.&nbsp; We believe that the proposed penalty amount is unfounded and without merit. With the help of local counsel we filed an appeal by the deadline of March&nbsp;15, 2013.&nbsp; We have argued that the amount due in connection with the matter, if any, is substantially less than that proposed by the SAT.&nbsp; In connection with the appeal, the SAT required us to post an appeal surety bond in the amount of roughly </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">321.0</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million pesos (approximately </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">$26.0</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million), which</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> amount reflects estimated additional penalties and interest if we are not successful on our appeal.&nbsp; This amount will be adjusted on an annual basis. We are currently awaiting a ruling from the Mexican courts.&nbsp; It is not possible at this time to predict the outcome of this matter or reasonably estimate any potential loss.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">As of December 31, 2013, we have accrued a total </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">of </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">$11.</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">8</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million relatin</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">g to these litigation matters and other disputes. We estimate that the ultimate resolution of these litigation matters and other disputes could result in a loss that is reasonably possible betwee</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">n &nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">$0</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> and </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">$10.6</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million in th</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">e aggregate, in excess of the amount accrued.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">Although we are subject to other litigation from time to time in the ordinary course of business, including employment, intellectual property and product liability claims, we are not party to any other pending legal proceedings that we believe will have a material adverse impact on our business, financial position, results of operations or cash flows.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">In July&nbsp;2013, the FASB issued ASU No.&nbsp;2013-11</font><font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;"> Income Taxes (Topic 740): Presentation of an Unrecognized Tax Benefit when a Net Operating Loss Carryforward, a Similar Tax Loss, or a Tax Credit Carryforward Exists</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> (&#x201C;ASU No.&nbsp;2013-11&#x201D;). This pronouncement provides guidance on financial statement presentation of an unrecognized tax benefit (&#x201C;UTB&#x201D;) when a net operating loss (&#x201C;NOL&#x201D;) carryforward, a similar tax loss or a tax credit carryforward exists. Under the pronouncement, an entity must present a UTB, or a portion of the UTB, in the financial statements as a reduction to a deferred tax asset (&#x201C;DTA&#x201D;) for an NOL carryforward, a similar tax loss or a tax credit carryforward except when:</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <div style="width:100%"><table style="width:100%;" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0"><tr><td style="width:18pt;"><p style="width:18pt;font-size:0pt;"></p></td><td valign="top" align="left" style="width: 18.00pt; display: inline;"> <p style="border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt;margin:0pt;"> <font style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;;"> 1)</font> </p> </td><td style="width:0pt;"><p style="width:0pt;width:0pt;font-size:0pt;"></p></td><td align="left" valign="top"> <p style="border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt;margin:0pt;"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">An NOL carryforward, a similar tax loss or a tax credit carryforward is not available as of the reporting date under the governing tax law to settle that would result from the disallowance of the tax position.</font></p></td></tr></table></div> <div style="width:100%"><table style="width:100%;" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0"><tr><td style="width:18pt;"><p style="width:18pt;font-size:0pt;"></p></td><td valign="top" align="left" style="width: 18.00pt; display: inline;"> <p style="border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt;margin:0pt;"> <font style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;;"> 2)</font> </p> </td><td style="width:0pt;"><p style="width:0pt;width:0pt;font-size:0pt;"></p></td><td align="left" valign="top"> <p style="border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt;margin:0pt;"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">The entity does not intend to use the DTA for this purpose (provided that the tax law permits a choice).</font></p></td></tr></table></div> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">If either of these conditions exists, an entity should present a UTB in the financial statements as a liability and should not net the UTB with a DTA. This amendment does not affect the amounts disclosed in the tabular reconciliation of the total amounts of UTBs because the tabular reconciliation presents gross amounts of UTBs. This pronouncement is effective for fiscal years and interim periods within those fiscal years beginning after December&nbsp;15, 2013. The Company will adopt the provisions of ASU No.&nbsp;2013-11 on January&nbsp;1, 2014. We do not anticipate the provisions of</font><font style="display: inline;"> ASU No.&nbsp;2013-11 will</font><font style="display: inline;"> have a material impact on to the Company&#x2019;s consolidated </font><font style="display: inline;">financial position or results of operations.</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> 658000 -299000 317704000 90625000 13160000 Our asset retirement obligation (&#x201C;ARO&#x201D;) liabilities are primarily associated with the disposal of property and equipment which we are contractually obligated to remove at the end of certain retail and office leases in order to restore the facilities back original condition as specified in the related lease agreements. We estimate the fair value of these liabilities based on current store closing costs and discount the costs back as if they were to be performed at the inception of the lease. At the inception of such leases, we record the ARO as a liability and also record a related asset in an amount equal to the estimated fair value of the obligation. The capitalized asset is then depreciated on a straight-line basis over the useful life of the asset. Upon retirement of the ARO liability, any difference between the actual retirement costs incurred and the previously recorded estimated ARO liability is recognized as a gain or loss in the consolidated statements of operations.</font><font style="display: inline;"> Our ARO liability as of </font><font style="display: inline;">December 31, 2013 and 2012</font><font style="display: inline;"> was $</font><font style="display: inline;">2.0</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;million and $</font><font style="display: inline;">2.4</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;million, respectively.</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> 63976000 57450000 92278000 104405000 8147000 15992000 36343000 36616000 81371000 97111000 10342000 14128000 10226000 12198000 104718000 98151000 19688000 14652000 307823000 321532000 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Advertising</font><font style="display: inline;">&#x2014;Advertising costs are expensed as incurred and production costs are generally expensed when the advertising is </font><font style="display: inline;">first </font><font style="display: inline;">run. 1100000 1400000 1000000 528000 1410000 1400000 10949000 3900000 200000 6600000 2400000 2000000 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">We record a liability equal to the fair value of the estimated future cost to retire an asset, if the liability&#x2019;s fair value can be reasonably estimated. Our asset retirement obligation (&#x201C;ARO&#x201D;) liabilities are primarily associated with the disposal of property and equipment which we are contractually obligated to remove at the end of certain retail and office leases in order to restore the facilities back original condition as specified in the related lease agreements. We estimate the fair value of these liabilities based on current store closing costs and discount the costs back as if they were to be performed at the inception of the lease. At the inception of such leases, we record the ARO as a liability and also record a related asset in an amount equal to the estimated fair value of the obligation. The capitalized asset is then depreciated on a straight-line basis over the useful life of the asset. Upon retirement of the ARO liability, any difference between the actual retirement costs incurred and the previously recorded estimated ARO liability is recognized as a gain or loss in the consolidated statements of operations.</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> 829638000 875159000 613115000 143236000 170426000 85756000 111785000 511203000 14489000 25738000 640077000 139855000 177343000 137701000 51155000 506054000 14093000 63743000 4022000 2368000 2165000 100000 100000 145583000 257587000 294348000 317144000 112004000 36761000 22796000 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Cash and Cash Equivalents</font><font style="display: inline;">&#x2014;Cash and cash equivalents represent cash and short-term, highly liquid investments with maturities of three months or less at the date of purchase. The Credit Agreement is available for working capital, capital expenditures, permitted acquisitions, reimbursement of drawings under letters of credit, and permitted dividends, distributions, purchases, redemptions and retirements of equity interests. Borrowings under the Credit Agreement are secured by all of our assets including all receivables, equipment, general intangibles, inventory, investment property, subsidiary stock and intellectual property. Borrowings under the Credit Agreement bear interest at a variable rate. For domestic rate loans, the interest rate is equal to the highest of (i)&nbsp;the daily federal funds open rate as quoted by ICAP North America, Inc. plus 0.5%, (ii)&nbsp;PNC&#x2019;s prime rate and (iii)&nbsp;a daily LIBOR rate plus 1.0%, in each case there is an additional margin ranging from 0.25% to 1.00% based on certain conditions. For LIBOR rate loans, the interest rate is equal to a LIBOR rate plus a margin ranging from 1.25% to 2.00% based on certain conditions. The Credit Agreement requires mo</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">nthly interest payments with respect to domestic rate loans and at the end of each interest period with respect to LIBOR rate loans. The Credit Agreement further provides for a limit on the issuance of letters of credit to a maximum of </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">$20.0</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million. The Credit Agreement cont</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">ains provisions requiring us to maintain compliance with certain restrictive and financial covenants.</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">As of December&nbsp;31, 2013 and 2012, we had </font><font style="display: inline;">no</font><font style="display: inline;"> outstanding borrowings under the Credit Agreement. As of each of December 31, 2013 and 2012, we </font><font style="display: inline;">had had issued and outstanding letters of credit of </font><font style="display: inline;">$7.2</font><font style="display: inline;"> million, which were reserved against the borrowing base under the terms of the Credit Agreement. During the years ended December 31, 2013, 2012 and 2011, we capitalized </font><font style="display: inline;">$0.1</font><font style="display: inline;"> million, </font><font style="display: inline;">$0.2</font><font style="display: inline;"> million and </font><font style="display: inline;">$0.</font><font style="display: inline;">4</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;m</font><font style="display: inline;">illion, respectively, in fees and third party costs which were incurred in connection with the Credit Agreement, as deferred financing costs. As of December&nbsp;31, 2013, we were in compliance with all restrictive financial and other covenants under the Credit Agreement.</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Long-term Bank Borrowings</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">On December 10, 2012, </font><font style="display: inline;">we </font><font style="display: inline;">entered into a Master Installment Payment Agreement (&#x201C;Master IPA&#x201D;) </font><font style="display: inline;">with PNC </font><font style="display: inline;">in which PNC finance</font><font style="display: inline;">s</font><font style="display: inline;"> the Company&#x2019;s purchase of software and services, which may include but are not limited to third party costs to design, install and implement software systems, and associated hardware described in the schedules defined within the Master IPA. This agreement was entered into to finance </font><font style="display: inline;">our</font><font style="display: inline;"> implementation of a new enterprise resource planning (&#x201C;ERP&#x201D;) system which began in October 2012 and is estimated to continue through late 2014. The terms of the agreement consist of variable interest rates and payment terms based on amounts borrowed and timing of activity throughout the implementation of the ERP</font><font style="display: inline;"> system</font><font style="display: inline;">. &nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">As of </font><font style="display: inline;">December 31, 2013 and 2012, </font><font style="display: inline;">we h</font><font style="display: inline;">ad </font><font style="display: inline;">$16.8</font><font style="display: inline;"> million and</font><font style="display: inline;"> &nbsp;$</font><font style="display: inline;">6.6</font><font style="display: inline;"> million, respectively, of long-term debt outstanding</font><font style="display: inline;"> under five and one separate notes payable</font><font style="display: inline;">, &nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">respectively, </font><font style="display: inline;">of wh</font><font style="display: inline;">ich </font><font style="display: inline;">$5.1</font><font style="display: inline;"> million and</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">$2.0</font><font style="display: inline;"> million, respectively, represent current installments</font><font style="display: inline;">. As of December 31, 2013, the notes bear interest rates ranging </font><font style="display: inline;">from </font><font style="display: inline;">2.45%</font><font style="display: inline;"> to </font><font style="display: inline;">2.79%</font><font style="display: inline;"> &nbsp;a</font><font style="display: inline;">nd maturities rangin</font><font style="display: inline;">g from </font><font style="display: inline;">September 2016</font><font style="display: inline;"> to </font><font style="display: inline;">September 2017</font><font style="display: inline;">. We </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">have </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">enter</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">ed</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> into foreign currency exchange forward contract</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> and currency swap derivative instruments </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">to selectively protect against volatility in the value of non-functional currency denominated monetary assets and liabilities, and of future cash flows caused by changes in foreig</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">n currency exchange rates. We do not designate these</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">derivative instruments</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> as hedging instruments under the accounting standards for derivatives and hedging.</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> Accordingly, these instruments are recorded at fair value as a derivative asset or liability on the balance sheet with their corresponding change in fair value recogniz</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">ed in &#x2018;Foreign currency transaction (gains) losses, net&#x2019; in our</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> consolidated statements of operations. F</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">or the year ended December 31</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">, 2011</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">, the n</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">et gain recognized of </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">$4.9</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">million recorded on the consolidated statements of operations is compr</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">ised of </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">a</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">$5.4</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million net gain</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> associated with exposure from day-to-day business transaction</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">s in various foreign currencies partially offset by a </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">$0.5</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million net loss</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> associated with our derivative instrument</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">s.</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Derivative Foreign Currency Contracts</font><font style="display: inline;">&#x2014;We are directly and indirectly affected by fluctuations in foreign currency rates which may adversely impact our financial performance. To mitigate the potential impact of foreign currency exchange rate risk, we may employ derivative financial instruments including forward contracts and option contracts. Forward contracts are agreements to buy or sell a quantity of a currency at a predetermined future date and at a predetermined rate. An option contract is an agreement that conveys the purchaser the right, but not the obligation, to buy or sell a quantity of a currency at a predetermined rate during a period or at a time in the future. These derivative financial instruments are viewed as risk management tools and are not used for trading or speculative purposes. We recognize derivative financial instruments as either assets or liabilities in the consolidated balance sheets and measure those instruments at fair value. Changes in the fair value of derivatives not designated or effective as hedges are recorded in &#x2018;Foreign currency transaction (gains)/losses, net&#x201D; in the consolidated statements of operations. We had no derivative instruments that qualified for hedge accounting during any of the periods presented. See Note&nbsp;7&#x2014;Fair Value Measurements and Financial Instruments for further discussion.</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> <div> <div basis followed by monthly vesting for the remaining three years.</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;">Restricted Stock </font><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;">Awards</font><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;"> and Units </font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">From time to time, we grant restricted stock </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">award</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">s &nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">(RSAs) </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">and restricted stock units</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> (RSUs)</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> to our employees. Unvested </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">RSAs</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> have the same rights as those of common shares including voting rights and non-forfeitable dividend rights. However, ownership of unvested </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">RSA</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">s cannot be transferred until they are vested. An unvested </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">RSU</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> is a contractual right to receive a share of common stock o</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">nly upon its vesting. RSUs have dividend equivalent rights which accrue over the term of the award and are paid if and when the RSUs vest, but they have no voting rights.</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">We typically grant time-based RSUs and performance-based RSUs. </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">Time-based RSUs are typically granted on an annual basis to certain non-executive employees and vest in </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">three</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> annual installments on a straight-line basis beginning one year after the grant date.</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> During the years ende</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">d December 31, 2013, 2012 and 2011, the board of directors approved grants of </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">0.4</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million, </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">0.4</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million and </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">0.2</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million of RSUs to certain non-executives. Perfor</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">mance-based RSUs are typically granted on an annual basis to certain executive employees and consist of a time-based and performance-based component. </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 14pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Separation Agreements</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">On December 27, 2013, John McCarvel resigned from his position as President, Chief Executive Officer (CEO) and director of the Company effective upon the earlier to occur of (i) April 30, 2014 or (ii) the Board&#x2019;s appointment of his successor as CEO. Also on December 27, 2013, the Company and Mr. McCarvel entered into a separation agreement providing that the Company will pay Mr. McCarvel (i) a </font><font style="display: inline;">$1.1</font><font style="display: inline;"> million separation payment on the first regularly scheduled payroll date after the effectiveness of his resignation and (ii) a </font><font style="display: inline;">$1.0</font><font style="display: inline;"> million separation payment on the first anniversary of the effectiveness of his resignation. In accordance with </font><font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;">ASC </font><font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;">420</font><font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;"> &#x2013; Exit or Disposal Cost Obligations</font><font style="display: inline;">, &nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">the Company will recognize first and second installment payments of </font><font style="display: inline;">$1.1</font><font style="display: inline;"> million and </font><font style="display: inline;">$1.0</font><font style="display: inline;"> million ratably from December 27, 2013 through April 30, 2014. If the separation date occurs prior to April 30, 2014 due to the appointment of a new CEO by the board of directors, the Company will consider the entire </font><font style="display: inline;">$2.1</font><font style="display: inline;"> million incurred and will expense the remaining portion on that date. Mr. McCarvel will also be entitled to receive any amount earned pursuant to the Company&#x2019;s 2013 annual incentive program, in such form and at such time as is provided under the terms of such program.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Mr. McCarvel also agreed to continue in a consulting capacity with the Company at his regular salary through April 30, 2014 if his successor is appointed prior to such date. Subject to continued service, Mr. McCarvel will be entitled to continued vesting through April 30, 2014 of the unvested portion of his existing restricted stock and restricted stock unit awards. Pursuant to the separation agreement, unvested share awards that are expected to vest through April 30, 2014 amounted to </font><font style="display: inline;">58,840</font><font style="display: inline;"> shares. </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;">Additionally, pursuant to the terms of the separation agreement, Mr. McCarvel forfeited </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;">388,745</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;"> share awards not expected to vest through April 30, 2014.</font><font style="display: inline;"> The separation payments are conditioned upon the effectiveness of Mr. McCarvel&#x2019;s release of claims in favor of the Company and his compliance with the non-competition, non-solicitation and confidentiality covenants contained in the separation agreement.</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> 1.27 0.32 1.46 0.68 0.50 -0.04 0.33 0.12 0.40 0.15 -0.76 1.24 0.31 1.44 0.68 0.49 -0.04 0.33 0.12 0.40 0.15 -0.76 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Earnings per Share</font><font style="display: inline;">&#x2014;Basic and diluted earnings per common share (&#x201C;EPS&#x201D;) is presented using the two-class method, which is an earnings allocation formula that determines earnings per share for common stock and any participating securities according to dividend rights and participation rights in undistributed earnings. Under the two-class method, EPS is computed by dividing the sum of distributed and undistributed earnings attributable to common stockholders by the weighted average number of shares of common stock outstanding during the period. A participating security is an unvested share-based payment award containing non-forfeitable rights to dividends and must be included in the computation of earnings per share pursuant to the two-class method. Shares of the Company&#x2019;s non-vested restricted stock awards are considered participating securities. Diluted EPS reflects the potential dilution from securities that could share in the earnings of the Company. Anti-dilutive securities are excluded from diluted EPS. See Note&nbsp;12&#x2014;Earnings per Share for further discussion.</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">12. This authorization effectively replaced the Company&#x2019;s previous stock repurchase authorizations. The number, price, structure and timing of the repurchases, if any, will be at the Company&#x2019;s sole discretion and future repurchases will be evaluated by the Company depending on market conditions, liquidity needs and other factors. Share repurchases may be made in the open market or in privately negotiated transactions. The repurchase authorization does not have an expiration date and does not oblige us to acquire any particular amount of our common stock. The Board may suspend, modify or terminate the repurchase program at any time without prior notice.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">During the three months ended December 31, 2013, we did not repurchase any shares associated with a publicly-announced repurchase plan. </table></div> <p style="margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt 6pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Non-Recurring Fair Value Measurements</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">The majority of our non-financial instruments, which include inventories, property and equipment and intangible assets, are not required to be carried at fair value on a recurring basis. However, if certain triggering events occur such that a non-financial instrument is required to be evaluated for impairment and the carrying value </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">is not recoverable, the carrying value would be adjusted to the lower of its cost or fair value and an impairment charge would be recorde</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">d. Se</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">e Note 2 &#x2013; Inventories, N</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">ote 3 &#x2013; Property and Equipment and Note 4 &#x2013; Goodwill &amp; Intangible Assets for discussions on impairment charges recorded during the periods presented.</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;">Fair Value</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&#x2014;Fair value is the price that would be received from the sale of an asset or transfer of a liability in an orderly transaction between market participants at the measurement date. When determining the fair value measurements for assets and liabilities which are required to be recorded at fair value, we consider the principal or most advantageous market in which a hypothetical sale or transfer would take place and consider assumptions that market participants would use when pricing the asset or liability, such as inherent risk, transfer restrictions, and risk of non-performance.</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">The fair value hierarchy is made up of three levels of inputs which may be used to measure fair value: </font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Level&nbsp;1&#x2014;observable inputs such as quoted prices for identical instruments in active markets;</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Level&nbsp;2&#x2014;observable inputs such as quoted prices for similar instruments in active markets, quoted prices for identical or similar instruments in markets that are not active and model derived valuations in which all significant inputs are observable in active markets; and </font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Level&nbsp;3&#x2014;unobservable inputs for which there is little or no market data and which require us to develop our own assumptions. We categorize fair value measurements within the fair value hierarchy based upon the lowest level of the most significant inputs used to determine such fair value measurement.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">Cash equivalents primarily include time deposits and certificates of deposit with original maturities of three months or less. Time deposits and certificates of deposit included in cash equivalents are valued at amortized cost, which approximates fair value. These investments have been classified as a Level 1 measurement.</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Derivative financial instruments are required to be recorded at their fair value, on a recurring basis. The fair values of our derivative instruments are determined using a discounted cash flow valuation model. The significant inputs used in the model are readily available in public markets or can be derived from observable market transactions, and therefore, have been classified as Level&nbsp;2. These inputs include the applicable exchange rates and forward rates, and discount rates based on the prevailing LIBOR deposit rates.</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Our other financial instruments are not required to be carried at fair value on a recurring basis. The carrying value of these financial instruments, including cash equivalents, accounts receivable, accounts payable and accrued liabilities, approximates fair value due to their short maturities. Based on borrowing rates currently available to us, with similar terms, the carrying values of capital lease obligations and the line of credit approximate their fair values.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Inventories and long-lived assets such as property and equipment and intangible assets are also not required to be carried at fair value on a recurring basis. For a discussion of inventory estimated fair value see &#x201C;Inventory Valuation&#x201D; below. However, when determining impairment losses, the fair values of property and equipment and intangibles must be determined. For such determination, we gene</font><font style="display: inline;">r</font><font style="display: inline;">ally use either an income approach with inputs that are mainly unobservable, such as expected future cash flows, or a market approach using observable inputs such as replacement cost or third party appraisals, as appropriate. Estimated future cash flows are based on management&#x2019;s operating budgets and forecasts which take into consideration both observable and unobservable inputs including growth rates, pricing, new markets and other factors expected to affect the business, as well as management&#x2019;s forecasts for inventory, receivables, capital spending, and other cash needs.</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">We consider this type of estimate to be classified as a Level 3 measurement. </font><font style="display: inline;">See Note&nbsp;6&#x2014;Fair Value Measurements for further discussion related to fair value measurements.</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> 49169000 4856000 3522000 33933000 6222000 636000 65633000 4548000 4272000 49665000 6439000 709000 5928000 16721000 7198000 14706000 13935000 13729000 106258000 4856000 6161000 87426000 7145000 670000 137850000 4548000 6501000 118940000 6878000 983000 57089000 2639000 53493000 923000 34000 72217000 2229000 69275000 439000 274000 P7Y P10Y P5Y 5548000 5548000 13501000 13501000 295000 295000 984000 984000 4886000 -2500000 -4678000 11892000 -13928000 6420000 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Foreign Currency Translation and Foreign Currency Transactions</font><font style="display: inline;">&#x2014;Our reporting currency is the U.S. dollar. Assets and liabilities of foreign operations denominated in local currencies are translated at the rate of exchange at the balance sheet date. Revenues and expenses are translated at the weighted average rate of exchange during the applicable period. Adjustments resulting from translating foreign functional currency financial statements into U.S. dollars are included in the foreign currency translation adjustment, a component of accumulated other comprehensive income in stockholders&#x2019; equity. </font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Gains and losses generated by transactions denominated in currencies other than the local functional currencies are reflected in the consolidated statement of operations in the period in which they occur and are primarily associated with payables and receivables arising from intercompany transactions.</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> 20827000 23653000 540000 -7200000 -13002000 2729000 2508000 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p><p style="page-break-after:always">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt;font-family:Times New Roman;;font-size: 10pt"><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;"></font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">4. <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Goodwill Impairment</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">We assess goodwill for impairment on an annual basis on the last day of the fourth quarter, or more frequently if events and circumstances indicate impairment may have occurred, at the reporting unit level. If the carrying value of the goodwill exceeds its implied fair value, we record an impairment loss equal to the difference. During the year ended December 31, 2013, we recorded </font><font style="display: inline;">$0.3</font><font style="display: inline;"> million of</font><font style="display: inline;"> goodwill impairment related to </font><font style="display: inline;">the retail channel</font><font style="display: inline;"> of our Crocs Benelux B.V. business purchased by our Crocs Stores B.V. subsidiary in July 2012. Goodwill and associated impairments are part of our Europe operating segment. During the years ended December 31, 2012 and 2011, we did not record any impairments related to goodwill.</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;">Intangible Assets</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&#x2014;Intangible assets that are determined to have finite lives are amortized over their useful lives on a straight-line basis. Customer relationships are amortized on a straight-line basis or an accelerated basis. Indefinite lived intangible assets, such as trade names, are not amortized and are evaluated for impairment at least annually and when circumstances imply possible impairment. </font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Amortization of manufacturing intangible assets is included in cost of sales on the consolidated statements of operations. Amortization related to corporate, non-product and non-manufacturing assets such as our global information systems is included in selling, general and administrative expenses on the consolidated statements of operations. The following table sets forth our definite lived intangible assets and the periods over which they are amortized.</font> </p> <div style="width:100%"><table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" align="center" style="border-collapse:collapse;width: 75.00%;margin-left:0pt;"> <tr> <td valign="bottom" style="width:215.00pt;padding:0pt 4.3pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 1pt;border-bottom:1pt solid #000000 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 8pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-size:8pt;">Intangible Asset Class</font></p> </td> <td valign="bottom" style="width:195.40pt;padding:0pt 4.3pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 1pt;border-bottom:1pt solid #000000 ;text-align:center;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 8pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-size:8pt;">Weighted Average Amortization Period</font></p> </td> </tr> <tr> <td valign="top" style="width:215.00pt;padding:0pt 4.3pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10pt;text-indent: -10pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="text-indent:0pt;margin-left:-10pt; Initial costs associated with internally-developed-and-used software are expensed until it is determined that the project has reached the application development stage. Once in its development stage, subsequent additions, modifications or upgrades to an internal-use software project are capitalized to the extent that they add functionality. Software maintenance and training costs are expensed in the period in which they are incurred. Capitalized software primarily consists of our enterprise resource system software, warehouse management software and point of sale software. At least annually, we consider the potential impairment of capitalized software by assessing the substantive service potential of the software, changes, if any, in the extent or manner in which the software is used or is expected to be used, and the actual cost of software development or modification compared to expected cost. See Note&nbsp;4&#x2014;Goodwill and Intangible Assets for further discussion.</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 31.5pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;">Impairment of Intangible Assets</font><font style="display: inline;">&#x2014;Intangible assets with indefinite lives are evaluated for impairment when events or changes in circumstances indicate that the carrying value may not be fully recoverable and at least annually. Intangible assets that are determined to have definite lives are amortized over their useful lives and are evaluated for impairment only when events or circumstances indicate a carrying value may not be fully recoverable. Recoverability is based on the estimated future undiscounted cash flows of the asset. If the asset is not supported on an undiscounted cash flow basis, the amount of impairment is measured as the difference between its carrying value and its </font><font style="display: inline;">estimated </font><font style="display: inline;">fair value.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Goodwill</font><font style="display: inline;">&#x2014;</font><font style="display: inline;">Goodwill</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;"> represents the excess purchase price paid over the fair value of assets acquired and liabilities assumed in acquisitions</font><font style="display: inline;">. Goodwill is considered an indefinite lived asset and therefore is not amortized.&nbsp; </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;">The Company assesses goodwill for impairment annually on the last day of the fourth quarter, or more frequently if events and circumstances indicate impairment may have occurred. If the carrying value of goodwill exceeds its implied fair value, the Company records an impairment loss equal to the difference. See </font><font style="display: inline;">Note&nbsp;4&#x2014;Goodwill</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;"> and Intangible Assets for discussion of goodwill balances and </font><font style="display: inline;">discussion of impairment losses recorded during the periods presented</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;">.</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> 300000 300000 536410000 144799000 607977000 196085000 160743000 106350000 165849000 623198000 200867000 153581000 102901000 500000 1400000 1410000 10600000 3861000 185000 6565000 10400000 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Impairment of Long-Lived Assets</font><font style="display: inline;">&#x2014;Long-lived assets to be held and used are evaluated for impairment when events or circumstances indicate the carrying value of a long-lived asset may not be fully recoverable. Events that may indicate the impairment of a long-lived asset (or asset group, as defined below) include (i)&nbsp;a significant decrease in its market price, (ii)&nbsp;a significant adverse change in the extent or manner in which it is being used or in its physical condition, (iii)&nbsp;a significant adverse change in legal factors or business climate that could affect its value, including an adverse action or assessment by a regulator, (iv)&nbsp;an accumulation of costs significantly in excess of the amount originally expected for its acquisition or construction, (v)&nbsp;its current period operating or cash flow losses combined with historical operating or cash flow losses or a forecast of its cash flows demonstrate continuing losses associated with its use, and (vi)&nbsp;a current expectation that, more likely than not, it will be sold or otherwise disposed of significantly before the end of its previously estimated useful life. If such facts indicate a potential impairment of a long-lived asset (or asset group), we assess the recoverability by determining if its carrying value exceeds the sum of its projected undiscounted cash flows from its use and eventual disposition over its remaining economic life. If the asset is not supported on an undiscounted cash flow basis, the amount of impairment is measured as the difference between its carrying value and its </font><font style="display: inline;">estimated </font><font style="display: inline;">fair value. Assets held for sale are reported at the lower of the carrying amount or fair value less costs to sell. Assets to be abandoned or from which no further benefit is expected are written down to zero at the time that the determination is made and the assets are removed entirely from service.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">An asset group is the lowest level of assets and liabilities for which identifiable cash flows are largely independent of the cash flows of other assets and liabilities.&nbsp;&nbsp;For assets involved in our retail business, our asset group is at the retail store level. See Note 3 &#x2013; Property and Equipment for a discussion of impairment losses recorded during the periods presented.</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> -12057000 12060000 -7818000 148747000 133488000 67777000 136690000 145548000 59959000 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 15pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p><p style="page-break-after:always">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 15pt;font-family:Times New Roman;;font-size: 10pt"><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;"></font><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">11. </td> <td valign="bottom" style="width:02.74%;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-left:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-right:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;height:12.75pt;padding:0pt;"> <p style="display: inline;">$</font></p> </td> <td valign="bottom" style="width:13.58%;border-top:1pt solid #000000 ;border-left:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:2pt double #000000 ;border-right:1pt none 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">We do not provide for deferred taxes on the excess of the financial reporting basis over the tax basis in our investments in foreign subsidiaries that are essentially permanent in duration. In general, it is our practice and intention to reinvest the earnings of our foreign subsidiaries in those operations. Generally, the earnings of our foreign subsidiaries become subject to U.S. taxation upon the remittance of dividends and under certain other circumstances. Exceptions may be made on a year-by-year basis to repatriate current year earnings of certain foreign subsidiaries based on cash needs in the U.S. As of </font><font style="display: inline;">December 31, 2013</font><font style="display: inline;">, we have provided for deferred U.S. incom</font><font style="display: inline;">e tax of $</font><font style="display: inline;">16.1</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;million on $</font><font style="display: inline;">7</font><font style="display: inline;">6</font><font style="display: inline;">.6</font><font style="display: inline;"> million of f</font><font style="display: inline;">oreign subsidiary earnings. No withholding tax is due with respect to the repatriation of these earnings to the U.S. and none has been provided for.</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">At </font><font style="display: inline;">December 31, 2013</font><font style="display: inline;">, U.S. income and foreign withholding taxes have not been provided on for approximately </font><font style="display: inline;">$474.2</font><font style="display: inline;"> million of unremitted earnings of subsidiaries operating outside of the U.S. These earnings are estimated to represent the excess of the financial reporting over the tax basis in our investments in those subsidiaries. These earnings, which are considered to be indefinitely reinvested, would become subject to U.S. income tax if they were remitted to the U.S. The amount of unrecognized deferred U.S. income tax liability on the unremitted earnings has not been determined because the hypothetical calculation is not practicable.</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">We have deferred tax assets related to certain deductible temporary differences in various tax jurisdictions for which we have recorded a valuation allowance </font><font style="display: inline;">o</font><font style="display: inline;">f $</font><font style="display: inline;">46.9</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;million against these defe</font><font style="display: inline;">rred tax assets because we do not believe that it is more likely than not that we will be able to realize these deferred tax assets. The significant components of the deferred tax assets for which a valuation allowance has been applied consist of net operating losses in certain tax jurisdictions for which management believes there is not sufficient positive evidence that such net operating losses will be realized against future income and book expenses not deductible for tax purposes in the current year such as inventory impairment reserves, equity compensation and unrealized foreign exchange loss that would increase such net operating losses in the same jurisdictions. These temporary differences are amounts which arose in jurisdictions where (i)&nbsp;current losses exist, (ii)&nbsp;such losses are in excess of any loss carryback potential, (iii)&nbsp;any tax planning strategies exist with which to overcome such losses are cost prohibitive and (iv)&nbsp;no profits are projected for the following year. For these reasons it is determined that it is more likely than not that these deferred tax assets will not be realized and a valuation allowance has been provided with respect to these deferred tax assets.</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">At December&nbsp;31, 2013, we had U.S. federal net operating loss carryforwards of $</font><font style="display: inline;">1.0</font><font style="display: inline;"> million, state net operating loss carryforwards of </font><font style="display: inline;">$96.5</font><font style="display: inline;"> million, charitable contribution carryforwards of $</font><font style="display: inline;">20.4</font><font style="display: inline;"> million and foreign tax credits of $</font><font style="display: inline;">4.0</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;million which will expire at various dates between 2014 and 2034. We do not believe that it is more likely than not that the benefit from certain federal and state net operating losses, and charitable contribution carryforwards will be realized. Consequently, we have a valuation allowance of $</font><font style="display: inline;">12.1</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;million on the deferred tax assets relating to these tax attributes. </font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">At December&nbsp;31, 2013, we have a foreign deferred tax asset of $</font><font style="display: inline;">16.0</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;million reflecting the benefit of $</font><font style="display: inline;">50.4</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;million in foreign net operating loss carryforwards, some of which have an indefinite life.&nbsp;&nbsp;We do not believe it is more likely than not that the benefit from certain foreign net operating loss carryforwards will be realized. Consequently, we have provided a valuation allowance of $</font><font style="display: inline;">14.5</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;million on the deferred tax assets relating to these foreign net operating loss carryforwards.</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">We had approximately $</font><font style="display: inline;">11.6</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;million in net deferred tax assets at December&nbsp;31, 2013. Approximately $</font><font style="display: inline;">7.6</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;million of the net deferred tax assets were located in foreign jurisdictions for which a sufficient history and expected future profits indicated that it is more likely than not that such deferred tax assets will be realized. Pre-tax profit of approximately $</font><font style="display: inline;">40.3</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;million is required to realize the net deferred tax assets.</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">At December&nbsp;31, 2013, approximately $</font><font style="display: inline;">1.8</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;million of net deferred tax assets consists of deferred tax assets related to estimated liabilities for uncertain tax positions that would be realized if such liabilities are actually incurred. The deferred tax assets represent primarily the reduction in tax expense that would occur upon an increase of intercompany royalty expense by various taxing authorities. Approximately $</font><font style="display: inline;">6.4</font><font style="display: inline;"> million of taxable income would have to be recognized to realize these deferred tax assets.</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">As a result of certain accounting realization requirements, the table of deferred tax assets and liabilities shown above does not include certain deferred tax assets at December&nbsp;31, 2013 that arose directly from tax deductions related to equity compensation in excess of compensation recognized for financial reporting. Equity will be increased by </font><font style="display: inline;">$11.5</font><font style="display: inline;"> million if and when such deferred tax assets are ultimately realized. We use ASC 740 with-and-w</font><font style="display: inline;">ithout ordering for</font><font style="display: inline;"> purposes of determining when excess tax benefits have been realized.</font> The state impact of any federal changes remains subject to examination by various state jurisdictions for a period up to two years after formal notification to the states.</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> 26632000 29385000 20274000 5613000 10630000 3900000 4400000 5000000 1000000 600000 600000 23902000 14205000 49539000 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Income Taxes</font><font style="display: inline;">&#x2014;Income taxes are accounted for using the asset and liability method which requires the recognition of deferred tax assets and liabilities for the expected future tax consequences of temporary differences between the carrying amounts and the tax basis of other assets and liabilities. We provide for income taxes at the current and future enacted tax rates and laws applicable in each taxing jurisdiction. We use a two-step approach for recognizing and measuring tax benefits taken or expected to be taken in a tax return and disclosures regarding uncertainties in income tax positions. We recognize interest and penalties related to income tax matters in income tax expense in the consolidated statement of operations. The contributions made were expensed at their fair value of $</font><font style="display: inline;">0.</font><font style="display: inline;">6</font><font style="display: inline;"> million, </font><font style="display: inline;">$1.7</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">million and </font><font style="display: inline;">$2.0</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">million, respectively. Also during the years ended </font><font style="display: inline;">December 31, 2013, 2012 and 2011</font><font style="display: inline;">, we recognized a gain of $</font><font style="display: inline;">0.</font><font style="display: inline;">1</font><font style="display: inline;"> million, $</font><font style="display: inline;">0.6</font><font style="display: inline;"> million and $</font><font style="display: inline;">0.7</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;million, respectively, and a net reduction of inventory of $</font><font style="display: inline;">0.</font><font style="display: inline;">5</font><font style="display: inline;"> million, $</font><font style="display: inline;">1.1</font><font style="display: inline;"> million and $</font><font style="display: inline;">1.3</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;million, respectively, as the fair value of the inventory contributed exceeded its carrying amount.</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> 155833000 154272000 164804000 162341000 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Inventory Valuation</font><font style="display: inline;">&#x2014;Inventories are valued at the lower of cost or market. Inventory cost is determined using the moving average cost method. At least annually</font><font style="display: inline;">, &nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;">or more frequently if events and circumstances indicate </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;">fair value is less than carrying value</font><font style="display: inline;">, we evaluate our inventory for possible impairment using standard categories to classify inventory based on the degree to which we believe that the products may need to be discounted below cost to sell within a reasonable period. We base inventory fair value on several subjective assumptions including estimated future demand and market conditions, as well as other observable factors such as current sell-through of our products, recent changes in demand for our products, global and regional economic conditions, historical experience selling through liquidation and price discounted channels and the amount of inventory on hand. If the estimated inventory fair value is less than its carrying value, the carrying value is adjusted to market value and the resulting impairment charge is recorded in &#x2018;Cost of sales&#x2019; on the consolidated statements of operations.
